				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">What does it mean to say that something &quot;uses&quot; a particular color space? The NES merely has particular waveforms that it outputs in response to palette indicies. These consist of either constant amplitude or a square wave of a particular phase between two amplitudes. Game programmers choose indicies based on what colors appear on a TV. They don't choose based on describing the NES circuitry as &quot;thinking&quot; of a particular color in a particular encoding space, outputting the proper phase of wave for it, then the TV decoding the phase and interpreting that as &quot;asking&quot; for a particular color, then converting that to RGB and displaying it.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
							</td>
						</tr>
						</table>
					</td>
				</tr>
